# Scoped unit tests only

**Never** run the full Jest suite for `onecgiar-pr-server` or `onecgiar-pr-client` (e.g. bare `npm run test` with no path filter, or broad patterns that cover the whole package).

**Always** scope tests to the module(s) / file(s) you changed:

```bash
# ✅ Server — only the touched module
cd onecgiar-pr-server && npm run test -- --testPathPattern="bilateral-center.service.spec"

# ✅ Client — only the touched module
cd onecgiar-pr-client && npm run test -- --testPathPattern="bilateral-auto-save.service.spec"

# ❌ Forbidden
cd onecgiar-pr-server && npm run test
cd onecgiar-pr-client && npm run test
cd onecgiar-pr-server && npm run test -- --testPathPattern="bilateral"   # too broad if many specs match
```

Rules of thumb:

- Prefer the co-located `*.spec.ts` for the exact file you edited.
- If multiple files in one feature changed, pass a narrow pattern that matches only those specs (pipe with `|` if needed).
- Do not use package-wide patterns like `.*` or empty `--testPathPattern`.
- Full-suite runs are only allowed when the user **explicitly** asks for them.
